It seems like you want to include a switch mechanism based on the type of argument during the argument parsing process. For this to be effective, we would typically recognize each argument type (like `Int`, `String`, `Bool`, etc.) and operate accordingly.

To properly apply a switch mechanism based on type during parsing, you'll have to implement a type-aware system within your argument parser. One common method for this is to use polymorphism, establishing a base `Arg` class that `Int`, `String`, `Bool`, and others inherit from, as well as using a virtual method that each derived class must implement for their specific parsing behavior.

Here's a simplified version of what the mechanism might look like in pseudo code:

```cpp
// This is a base class for all argument types
class Arg {
public:
    virtual bool ParseValue(const std::string& arg_string) = 0; // Pure virtual function
    // ... other functions and members
};

// Derived class overrides the ParseValue method for string arguments
class StringArg : public Arg {
public:
    bool ParseValue(const std::string& arg_string) override {
        value_ = arg_string;
        return true;
    }
    // ... members like value_
};

// Derived class overrides the ParseValue method for int arguments
class IntArg : public Arg {
public:
    bool ParseValue(const std::string& arg_string) override {
        try {
            value_ = std::stoi(arg_string);
            return true;
        } catch(const std::invalid_argument&) {
            return false; // Parsing failed, invalid input
        }
    }
    // ... members like value_
};

