In the `Parse` method, you iterate over each argument string, separate their keys and values, find the corresponding `Arg` object, and then call its `ParseValue` method with the value string. Each derived class will provide its own implementation on how to parse their respective value strings.

This setup allows you to have a clear separation between the functionality for each type of argument and an easier mechanism to handle new argument types you might want to add in the future. Remember that this example is quite abstract and simple, so you'll have to adapt it to your particular code structure and requirements.

To use an enum to specify argument types within your argument parser, you can create an enum to represent the different types of arguments your parser can handle, and then utilize this to drive the parsing logic.

Here is how you could integrate an `enum` for argument types into your existing argument parser's structure:

First, define the enum for your argument types:

```cpp
